Attached to this email is an ISO file that contains your payload and a decoy document with the deal's details. (if:$recon_domain_name is true)[ Your email is convincing, you can see with the tracking pixel that it has been forwarded. You receive ping-backs from residential home IPs. A chance that you included a guardrail and only let the malware execute on a computer if it is joined to the ingen.corp domain. All that reconnaissance phase was useful after all! ] (else:)[Your email is convincing. You get a shell, then a second and even a third one... but you quickly notice that something is wrong. The first 2 shells are coming from private computers of the employees and the last one is from another company. InGen's IT security has been notified by a single vigilant user that the email was malicious. But before that, another user has forwarded your email to many of his contacts. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[Good luck explaining to this third party company why you have infected their computer with your malware. Game over.]] [[Try something else|Let's go phishing]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)How would you like to try to gain your first foothold in the company? ❤️[[Let's go phishing]] (if:$recon_lab_tour is true)[🟩[[Let's get physical]]](else-if: $recon_offices is true)[🟩[[Let's get physical]]] (if:$recon_saas_erp is true)[🔵[[Let's do a supply chain attack]]] ⭐[[I changed my mind, I want to do recon first|Do some recon first]]The bad thing when you go fast is that you generate more noise. With the amount of connections you generated, you were easy to spot for the Blue Team. They monitor the number of access to different shares per hour. As you accessed most of them in the last hour, they got alerted. It took them some time to confirm with the owner of the compromised machine that he wasn't causing this activity. But as soon as this was done, they investigated, found out that the process causing this amount of connections isn't supposed to do that. Suspecting something malicious, they isolated the host. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[Now they have backtracked to the persistence method you used and are creating custom rules. The exercise was useful, but it's over now. Game over.] [[Try something else|Find more information about the company systems]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)You browse the local file system, this is often a good way to discover what the user is doing. You find the documents he's working on, avoid looking at private data because you know it is forbidden in the rules of engagement. There's not much on that host, no `passwords.txt` or password manager. You still discover that a top tier EDR is installed and that Sysmon is running too. Now you're warned, you will have to operate carefully! [[Back to post-exploitation|Post-exploitation]]Now as a Red Team professional, unless you provide a good report and debrief the whole exercise with the defending teams, your work isn't worth more than what a real attacker would do. With that in mind, you set yourself to work again... on the report 😁You call the IT support and informs that you have an issue on this server. You ask them to log in to check the problem. They ask to take remote control over your session. As you only have a C2 channel you cannot provide them access. [[Hang up and try something else|Plant a malicious DLL next to a service executable]]That would be a terrific target, an adversary achieving that would be practically assured of staying in the target's environment forever. However, to protect the good relationship they have with the Blue Team, InGen's management refuses this proposition. [[Propose something else|Intro]]It works, you have a connection to the database. You enumerate the data but don't find anything useful for your objectives. The account has no useful privileges, you can only access the database data. You have to move further: ❤️[[Connect to the server via RDP with the service account]] 🟩[[Connect to the server using remote PowerShell]]It works, you're connected and you soon notice that your account is also a local administrator on this server. You know that it will be useful to maintain access to this server for a longer period of time. You proceed to [[Install persistence]] on the server.This is not the best idea you had, the account is allowed to connect and you get a session. But the Blue Team has a detection for service accounts connecting using RDP. They detected you. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[The account's password has been reset and your implant died because the machine was isolated.] [[Try something else|Search in the internal Git repositories]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)You plug your hardware implant in the ethernet port next to the printer. You validate that you can reach the device from the 4G network card, it works. You validate that you get an IP address on the internal network, it works. You leave the building excited, your implant seems to be working, the NAC didn't block you. This is going to be fun! A few hours later, you're back to the office. You start exploring the network from the hardware implant but you can't see anything not a single device is answering to your scans, you literally are alone in the network. InGen, knowing the lack of NAC is a problem, has implemented a micro-segmentation approach. You can't do anything from that subnet, except reach the print server... but you don't even know the IP address. 1.5 days later, your implant stops responding, InGen had a social engineering assessment last year. They recommended to regularly search for a list of known suspicious MAC addresses connecting to the network. The Raspberry Pi network card is on this list. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[It triggered an alert and someone has now unplugged your device and is running forensic tests on it. Game over.] [[Try something else|Attempt initial access]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)You turn around the corner and a woman with a lab coat asks you what you're doing here. She has a badge mentioning "Research Officer", and immediately sees that you're not at your place here. She brings you back to the reception and outside of the building. [[Try something else|Attempt initial access]]InGen's management accepts your proposition. They provide a short list of information that should never get in the hands of their competitors. You agree on time limits for the engagement and on communication ways. You're all set to go. How will you start your Red Team Operation (RTO)? ❤️[[Attempt initial access]] 🟩[[Do some recon first]]You have some time until the beginning of the project and you can use it to gain more insights on your target. Wikipedia tells you that //"International Genetics Incorporated or InGen, is a bioengineering start-up company founded by John Hammond and Benjamin Lockwood. This company performs research to recreate extinct animals, with the aim to clone those creatures."// You need more information, what will you use? ❤️[[Search on LinkedIn]] 🟩[[Look for credentials on the Darknet]] 🔵[[Scrape all public websites of the company for documents]] ⭐[[Look for office locations of InGen in the country]]Sadly for you, this is a common behavior from adversaries, many detections exist and are classified as high severity alerts. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[Your tool was detected, the incident responders are after you. Game over.] [[Try something else|Kill a service of the server to force an intervention]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)You know that Active Directory is deployed and widely used. And you know that often, there are misconfigurations, and paths to escalate privileges in here. You choose to explore that route, but how do you do that? ❤️[[Run BloodHound]] 🟩[[Perform a Kerberoasting attack]] 🔵[[Run a few custom queries to learn about the AD|Find some useful bit of information]] ⭐[[Use SOCKS to browse with ADexplorer|Find some useful bit of information]]This is an example question, which choice would you make? ❤️Red heart 🟩Green square 🔵Blue circle ⭐Yellow starYou decide to start having a look at InGen's internal documentation. From the user's bookmarks and the connected drives, you have several options to look for information. ❤️[[Search in the internal wiki]] 🟩[[Enumerate the Active Directory]] 🔵[[Search in the network shares]] ⭐[[Search in the internal Git repositories]]You remember discussing with many other red teamers, and everyone told you that knowing your target is key to a successful operation. So you want to learn as much as you can on the company and their IT systems. The question is, how do you do that? ❤️[[List processes]] 🟩[[Browse local files]] 🔵[[Run shell commands (whoami, ipconfig, net users, ...)]] ⭐[[Prompt the user for his password]]While looking at the structure of the Active Directory you notice that there's a group named `global_adm_servers`, this looks like a good target for you to gain access to the information you need and move towards your objective. [[Find more information about the company systems]]You propose that you go after the highest level of privileges in the company. The domain admin. However, InGen tells you that they have done that already and they don't need another internal pentest. [[Propose something else|Intro]]You don't even have the time to run the executable. As soon as it's dropped on the disk, it's spotted by the antivirus, it's deleted and an alert is generated. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[It won't be long until the Blue Team kills your access. Game over.] [[Try something else|Install persistence]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)Do you think you know enough to start playing? <img width="300px" src="data:image/png;base64, It works ! The user gives you his password, it's not a simple password, you would never have guessed or cracked it. 41 minutes later, however, your connection dies. The tool you chose to run, even if obfuscated, was recognized as malicious by a custom detection created by the Blue Team on the PowerShell script logs. It was flagged as a high-severity alert and the incident responders isolated the computer and had the user reset his password. It won't be useful to you now. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[You lost your access and have to start over. Game over.] [[Try something else|Post-exploitation]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)BloodHound is a great tool for red teamers and defenders alike, but it's also well-known. By know, many companies have developed ways to detect the tool when it's run with the default settings. At InGen, they have a special object configured to alert when it's accessed. As BloodHound ran your data collection, it queried for that object and an alert was triggered. A few minutes later, the incident responders were verifying from which machine and process the query came. They noticed that many other complex queries had been run which is a typical sign of Active Directory enumeration. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[They isolated the machine and are performing forensic analysis on it. Game over.] [[Try something else|Find more information about the company systems]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)You run your commands: `ipconfig: 172.17.42.71` `whoami: INGEN\U018322` The user isn't a local administrator, no luck. However, you see that he could have some interesting privileges based on the Active Directory group memberships. Everything seems to go fine until your implant stops responding. Maybe it's just the end of the user's workday... but the next day the implant doesn't come back online. What you ran is the typical playbook of several ransomware actors. Detections are well-tested. An alarm triggered and around 30 minutes later, the host was contained by the SOC. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[They are doing further analysis at the moment, but don't expect to see your implant coming back. Game over.] [[Try something else|Post-exploitation]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)You clone the PoC from Github on your development machine and compile it. It works on the first attempt and after testing it, grants you SYSTEM level privileges on your development machine. You proceed to obfuscate it heavily to make it bypass every antivirus on Virustotal. You run the exploit and get a new implant connecting with SYSTEM level privileges. It's now late at night and you go to bed, knowing that you can run that same exploit tomorrow. The next day, you wake up with several vocal messages from your contact at InGen. They were contacted by a security researcher via the security@ingen.com email address. The PoC you found on Github was trojanized and covertly sent back some information to the researcher who then contacted InGen. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[The case was escalated to the CISO, as he was informed about the Red Team, he told your contact. Both are very unhappy, your mission is aborted. Game over.] [[Try something else|Post-exploitation]] Note: This is a real thing, it recently happened and the PoC installed a malware named VenomRAT: https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/fake-cve-2023-40477-poc-hides-venomrat/ (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)You don't get passwords, or even NT hashes... They must be using Credential Guard. You should have checked that before, luckily you weren't detected because of this mistake. You make a note to mark this as a positive point in your report. You remember that mimikatz can do more than `sekurlsa::logonpasswords` maybe you could use it to steal Kerberos tickets instead. [[Try something else|Kill a service of the server to force an intervention]]While searching through the numerous websites of InGen, you only find documents with public information. You notice a contact form to ask for information about tours of the research lab. But the really interest is in the metadata, Now you know the name of the internal domain (ingen.corp) and how the usernames are formatted (U123456). ❤️[[Do more recon|Do some recon first]] 🟩[[Attempt initial access]] (set: $recon_domain_name to true) (set: $recon_lab_tour to true)Credentials stored in source code is a bad practice of course. But you know it happens more often than not. Armed with that hope, you search for various types of credentials and find a database connection string: `Server=SRV-T-DB0121;Database=TEST02;User Id=LocalTest;Password=burp<>BEEF;` What will you do with that information? ❤️[[Connect to the database from the attacker machine]] 🟩[[Connect to the server via RDP with the service account]] 🔵[[Connect to the server using remote PowerShell]] To search in the internal wiki, you enable a feature called SOCKS, this allows you to tunnel your connection through the compromised machine up to your attacker machine. With that, you can browse the wiki comfortably from your attacker's machine. You issue some search keywords looking for passwords and access keys and you soon find an account with its password on a project page: - User: `INGEN\TECH_SRVADM` - Pass: `8URP-15-N0T-833F` According to the wiki page, it should be a local administrator for several servers. ❤️[[Test the account with a connection to a domain controller|This was a canary account]] 🟩[[Connect to one of the server with RDP|This was a canary account]] 🔵[[Connect to one of the server with SMB|This was a canary account]] ⭐[[Connect to one of the server with remote PowerShell|This was a canary account]]You've seen multiple times that networks shares can contain sensitive information accessible by everyone in the company. With that in mind, you search for files on InGen's fileshares. What do you choose? ❤️[[Manual enumeration]] 🟩[[Automated enumeration]]You find multiple profiles of InGen employees. You get information on what kind of technology they use, and on some of their vendors too. In particular, you see that they use a SaaS ERP. ❤️[[Do more recon|Do some recon first]] 🟩[[Attempt initial access]] (set: $recon_saas_erp to true)InGen has custom detections on their email gateway that trigger if an email is trying to spoof one of their senior executives. Your email falls in that trap, it is reviewed by the security team and discarded as a scam. [[Try something else|Let's go phishing]]Where it all begins. Let's have an example question to make sure you understand the game system. [[Go for it!]]The corridor leads to several lab rooms with glass doors. In the corridor, you see a multifunction printer, there's also a laptop on the table next to it. ❤️[[Grab the laptop and head towards the exit]] 🟩[[Connect your hardware implant next to the printer]]The corridor leads to multiple glass doors, each one with some laboratory equipment. Nothing sparks your interest in the rooms. [[Continue around the corner]]D is for dice. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[Game over.] [[Try again|Go for it!]]You chose to target the branch office. It's a shared building because InGen doesn't need all the space in there. It's early in the night, it's cold and you try to find an open window or a door. There's none so you resort to a trick that you've learned on youtube, open a double door from the inside as there's a motion sensor. You send some smoke through the space between the doors and after the third attempt, they open! You enter and when opening the next door, you hear the alarm ring. 10 minutes later the police arrives. You try to explain that you were allowed to break in. They still take you and your colleague in custody for the night. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[It will take 5 months to settle the legal case. Game Over.] [[Try something else|Attempt initial access]] Based on a true story: https://www.darkreading.com/vulnerabilities-threats/pen-testers-who-got-arrested-doing-their-jobs-tell-all (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)It's close to Christmas so you find it cool to try to break in the office with a Santa Claus disguise. Further, it allows you to hide implants and all the necessary equipment under the chocolate, mandarins and peanuts. What you didn't know, is that InGen hired someone to do exactly this job, and they were faster than you. The employee at the desk tells you that this happened already and you're escorted out of the building. [[Try something else|Attempt initial access]]The research lab looks like an older building, and they propose tours of the facility. It looks plausible that you can break in. After watching the main entrance, you notice that employees come back after their lunch in large groups and that not everyone need to use their badge. Further, the reception desk is closed for lunch, too. You come back the next day and act like you belong to one of those groups to "tailgate" in the building. Sometimes the easiest solutions are the best, too. [[You enter the main hall|Main hall]]You've just fallen into one of the Blue Team's traps. This account is what they name a canary. It is placed here as an enticing target for an attacker looking into the wiki. As soon as you've authenticated with the account, it triggered a critical severity alert. The incident responders contacted the victim user in the next 15 minutes and after confirming he doesn't know of this activity, they isolated the machine. (text-colour:red)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[They are doing further analysis at the moment, but don't expect to see your implant coming back. Game over.] [[Try something else|Find more information about the company systems]] (set: $death_count to $death_count+1)This is one of the most obvious persistence method, and still, with the amount of things happening in a company (the noise), it can be hard to spot. While looking at the existing tasks, you spot one that is suspicious. Looking more closely, it launches a binary and several libraries that looks suspicious too. After taking a closer look at the binaries and running them through a sandbox, you are almost certain that you found someone else having a remote access to this server. You immediately contact InGen and inform them. They will now onboard an external incident response company to handle the case. (text-colour:green)+(size:1.5)+(box:"=XxXxX=")[The exercise is over for now, but it was very useful for your customer.] [[Try something else|Install persistence]]You start with a simple question about the lab tour, pretending to plan a visit with a retirement house. You wonder if it is accessible for people in a wheelchair, if there are toilets accessible for the public, etc... After some additional exchanges, you send them a full document explaining in more details what are your requirements for the accessibility of the location. In that document, you have hidden your malware. The user opens the document and unknowingly saves your malware to disk. It worked and the next day, when the user reboots the computer, you have an implant running! [[Continue to post-exploitation|Post-exploitation]]It takes time and you have a limited time frame to finish this project. You must go faster. [[Try something else|Plant a malicious DLL next to a service executable]]This is a cool idea, it would work, if the user was authenticating locally or with RDP. But here, they use the company's dedicated tool to logon remotely and it's immune to this attack. [[Try something else|Kill a service of the server to force an intervention]] Note: here's the tool https://github.com/gtworek/PSBits/tree/master/PasswordStealing/NPPSpyYou get a long list of Kerberos tickets. While sifting through them, you find the one that is of interest to you. It's the TGT of this user who is a member of `global_adm_servers`. With that, you can request service tickets and gain access to anything this user has access to, until the expiration of the ticket. And this is in 10 hours, do not waste time ! From the reconaissance, you know the name of the server that should contain the data you're looking for. With the credentials you will now try to move laterally to that server. It's in a restricted zone and you have to move through a jump host... but it's not a big issue as the `global_adm_servers` group has administrative privileges on the jump host too. After those additional hops, you finally reach the server where InGen stores their most sensitive data. And now that you have a reliable C2 channel to that server it's easy for you to access the data and take a few screenshots as a proof. You don't exfiltrate the data as it was not part of the objectives. After a short celebration, you phone your contact at InGen and inform him of your success.
